To rewrite each expression so that all exponents are positive, apply the negative–exponent rule ( x^{−n}=1/x^{\,n} ) and the power‐of‐a‐power rule ( (x^{m})^{n}=x^{\,m n} ).

a) s^{−8}  
   = 1 / s^{8}

b) (a^{9})^{−10}  
   = a^{9(−10)}          (power of a power)  
   = a^{−90}  
   = 1 / a^{90}

Thus

a) s^{−8}=1/s^{8}  
b) (a^{9})^{−10}=1/a^{90}

Use the rule  x^{−n}=1/x^{n}  (for x≠0) and remember that the exponent −4 applies only to the factor it is written on.

a) (2q)^{−4}
   = 1/(2q)^{4}
   = 1/(2^{4}q^{4})
   = 1/(16q^{4})

b) 2q^{−4}
   = 2·1/q^{4}
   = 2/q^{4}

c) −2q^{−4}
   = −2·1/q^{4}
   = −2/q^{4}

So the simplified forms are
a) 1/(16q^{4}), b) 2/q^{4}, c) −2/q^{4}.

Remember the product rule for exponents with the same base:  

  a^m · a^n = a^{m+n}  

and the meaning of a negative exponent:  

  a^{−k} = 1 / a^{k}  (for a ≠ 0).

Let y ≠ 0.

a) y^{5} · y^{−5}  
 = y^{5 + (−5)}  
 = y^{0}  
 = 1

b) y · y^{5}  
 = y^{1 + 5}  
 = y^{6}

c) y · y^{−5}  
 = y^{1 + (−5)}  
 = y^{−4}  
 = 1 / y^{4}

Answers:  
a) 1  b) y^6  c) 1 / y^4
